WHITE WINE QUALITY “SRIJON SARKAR”

In this dataset, we will be exploring the different features of white wine. We shall compare the different attributes with the quality of the wine itself and try to learn which features are most correlated with it.

It makes sense to convert it into a factor variable.

What we observe here is that although wine quality ranges from 0-10, we only have qualities in 3-9 in our dataset. Also, count of quality 3 and 9 wine is very low. The highest count of white wine is of quality 6.

Now lets look at the distribution of density in the different wine samples.

We can get a decent idea of the distribution here, but most values are centered just below 1, and rest of the plot has outliers.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

This plot is a better visualisation. We notice that most peaks are just above 0.99, and all counts above 200 are between 0.99 and 1.

Let us plot the histogram of alcohol variable and see its distribution.

This histogram tells us that a large no. of our samples have alcohol% just below 10. All the alcohol% values lie between 8 and 14. Let us plot a boxplot and compare the values with different qualities of white wine.

Most white wine samples in our dataset have fixed acidity levels around 6.5 g/dm^3.

All our samples have volatile acidity values below 0.8 g / dm^3, and maximum samples have between 0.2 and 0.3 values.

It refers to the total sulfur dioxide contents of white wine, including free and bound forms. It is centered around 120 mg / dm^3.

Most free sulfur dioxide values are around the 25 mg / dm^3 mark.

The residual sugar is measured in g / dm^3 , and we can see that maximum samples in our dataset have residual sugar amount below 2.5 .

Chlorides is the amount of salt in wine, measured in g/ dm^3, and most of our samples have below 0.05

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The white wine quality dataset has 4898 no. of samples, with each sample associated with 12 features( +1 which is indices). The output variable is the quality of each sample which can ideally have a number from 0 to 10, however our dataset only has samples qualities lying between 3 and 9. The maximum no. of samples belong to quality 6.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I am interested mostly in the quality factor, and the features which help in driving that quality upwards, that is which variables are highly correlated with the quality factor.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The alcohol% , pH and density seem to be important variables with respect to determining the quality, and hence will concentrate on them. But will look for correlations in other variables too.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No, I did not create any new variable.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form  of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Yes, I converted the type of data for the quality factor. Since it took a discrete value from the set(0,10), I converted it into a factor variable. That’s the only change I did in the dataset.

Bivariate Plots Section

Let us first plot fixed.acidity vs volatile.acidity, and check if there is any correlation between the two.

Based on this plot, it doesn’t seem that there is any correlation in between the variables. Let us find the correlation coeficient of the same.

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  df$fixed.acidity and df$volatile.acidity
## t = -1.5886, df = 4896, p-value = 0.1122
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.050671536  0.005312543
## sample estimates:
##         cor 
## -0.02269729

The value of correlation coefficient is too low to be considered significant. Hence we can conclude that there isn’t any correlation between them.

Let us see if the density changes along with the quality of wine. Let us make a box plot for the different wine qualities.

We can see that the median value of density of the white wine generally gets lower as the quality of the wine increases. Although there are quite a few outliers of lower quality which also show similar density as higher quality wines. Let us find the actual numerical differences in the median values.

let us plot a boxplot of different pH values of the different qualities and find the differences, if any.

It is somewhat similar to the above plot. Just like how alcohol% decreases from quality level 3 to 5 and then increases, median pH values follows the same trend. This means that there could be some kind of correlation between pH and alcohol%. Let us plot these 2 variables on a scatter plot and see if any correlation exists.

The plot seems very spread out and dispersed. The correlation coefficient of these features must be quite low. It seems unlikely that any correlation exists; however we’ll find the pearson’s correlation coefficient anyway.

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  df$pH and df$alcohol
## t = 8.5601, df = 4896, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.09374446 0.14893205
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1214321

The correlation is quite low in these two variables; so there isn’t any causation between the two, but these 2 variables do cause another variable(quality).

Apart from that, we saw that higher quality wines have higher pH values(more basic). This could mean that higher quality wines have lesser acidic properties. Let us plot a box plot of fixed acidity against the qualities.

There is a very small but appreciatable decrease in the fixed acidity levels, as the quality increases. However, it is not significant enough.

Now lets plot free.sulfur.dioxide vs total.sulfur.dioxide . Without seeing the plot, we know that there must be a correlation between the two, as total sulfur dioxide takes account of the free sulfur dioxide already.

Just as we felt, the plot does signify a strong correlation between the 2 features. Lets find the correlation coeficient between them.

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  df$free.sulfur.dioxide and df$total.sulfur.dioxide
## t = 54.645, df = 4896, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5977994 0.6326026
## sample estimates:
##      cor 
## 0.615501

We can see that the correlation value is quite high. Hence we can conclude that there is a strong correlation between the two, and a causation of course, as total sulfur dioxides accounts for free and bound forms of SO2.

As we can see the correlation factor is a negative high value, which means that they are strongely negatively correlated. Thus, we infer that as the alcohol% increases in the wine sample, its density decreases.

Multivariate Plots Section

We’ve seen that higher quality of wine have got lower amounts of densities, while having pH and alcohol%. So let us plot alcohol vs pH for the different qualities first.

Most blue spots, which correspond to high quality, are found at the right side of the scatter plot, which means high % alcohol. However, no visible trend is present corresponding to the pH values for lower or higher quality wines.

Now let us plot density vs alcohol vs quality

This plot is spread out similar to the above plot. The lighter spots are concentrated to the left, and darker ones in the right of the scatter plot. Blue spots are to the right and below spots meaning high alcohol and lower densities, so high quality wines have higher qualities of wine and lower densities.

It is somewhat hard to conclude something concrete from this plot, as the light green spots are all over the plot. However, we can see most darker spots are to the left of the plot, signifying lower density values for high quality wines.

In this plot, we see that pure blue colour spots are present only at the top left region, which means lowest values of density corresponds to high percentage of alcohol and low amounts of residual sugar. As the amount of sugar increases and alcohol decreases, the spot colour changes towards red, which means high density.

It seems as if residual sugar and alcohol are good estimators for the density variable. Let’s try to fit a linear model to this.

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = density ~ alcohol + residual.sugar, data = df)
## 
## Residuals:
##        Min         1Q     Median         3Q        Max 
## -0.0020196 -0.0005852 -0.0001403  0.0004674  0.0249805 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)     1.005e+00  1.349e-04  7446.7   <2e-16 ***
## alcohol        -1.226e-03  1.189e-05  -103.2   <2e-16 ***
## residual.sugar  3.607e-04  2.884e-06   125.1   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.0009137 on 4895 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9067, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9067 
## F-statistic: 2.379e+04 on 2 and 4895 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Just the alcohol and residual sugar variables account for 90% of variance in density variable.

We see here that the red spots are concentrated to the left and lower parts of the scatter plot, which means higher pH values have lower fixed and volatile acidity values. This is expected, as high pH values correspond to lesser acidic properties.

Not exactly strengthened, as most scatter plots which took on colours corresponding to quality levels were not linearly seperable. Generally it was visible that high quality wines have lower density, higher alcohol% and higher pH values.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

Yes, I created a linear model starting from the residual sugar and the alcohol% to the density.

The variables in the linear model account for 90.7% of the variance in the density of white wine. I have used only 2 variables in this model; there must be more variables which affect the density variable.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

What we observe here is the variation in alcohol% in the different quality levels of white wine. While there is a slight decrease from quality 3 to 5, from there it increases significantly to the highest quality.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot is significant as it shows the variation in density as a function of alcohol and residual sugar. Fitting these to a linear model gave us one in which alcohol and residual sugar accounted for 90% variation in density.

Plot Three

Description Three

This plot shows the variation of quality with pH and alcohol% . Just as we had seen before, higher quality wines(8,9) have higher alcohol% than quality levels 5,6,7, however, even quality 3,4 have higher alcohol% than 5,6,7. This shows that in some features(alcohol, pH, chlorides and fixed acidity) quality 3 and 4 contradict the trend and have characteristics similar to the higher qualities.

Reflection

In this exploration of white wine dataset, my main aim was to determine which features actually increase the quality of white wine. The alcohol%, density and chlorides turned out to be significant variables on simple boxplot analysis. Apart from these, density variable turned out to be highly dependent on residual sugar and alcohol %. Most of the multivariate analysis plots were not very conclusive as quality level 3 and 4 displayed properties similar to higher quality levels in some features. Also, the dataset had very few samples of quality 3,4, 8 and 9. A huge number of samples belonged to level 6 and 7. This dataset is quite old(2009) and it should be updated with new samples of low and high qualities. Also we know that the quality of white wine can range from 0-10, however our dataset only contains samples of quality 3-9.
